# Purpose     : Configuration file for dircolors
# Last Update : Sun 24 Nov 2019 01:07:28 PM CET
# =========================================================================
# Configuration file for dircolors, a utility to help you set the
# LS_COLORS environment variable used by GNU ls with the --color option.
# Copyright (C) 1996, 1999-2008
# Free Software Foundation, Inc.
# Copying and distribution of this file, with or without modification,
# are permitted provided the copyright notice and this notice are
# preserved. The keywords COLOR, OPTIONS, and EIGHTBIT (honored by the
# slackware version of dircolors) are recognized but ignored.
# Below, there should be one TERM entry for each termtype that is
# colorizable
#
# Modern terminals support 256 colors.
# Text 256 color coding:
# 38;5;COLOR_NUMBER
# Background 256 color coding:
# 48;5;COLOR_NUMBER

# =========================================================================
# TYPES
# =========================================================================
NORMAL      00       ## Global default
FILE        00       ## Regular file
DIR         01;34    ## Directory
LINK        01;36    ## Symbolic Link
EXEC        01;32    ## This is for files with execute permission
#FIFO       00       ## Pipe
#SOCK       00       ## Socket
#DOOR       00       ## Door
#BLK        00       ## Block device driver
#CHR        00       ## Character device driver
#ORPHAN     00       ## Symlink to nonexistent file, or non-stat'able file
#SETUID     00       ## File that is setuid (u+s)
#SETGID     00       ## File that is setgid (g+s)
#STICKY     00       ## Dir with sticky bit set (+t) and not other-writable
#CAPABILITY 00       ## File with capability
#HARDLINK   00       ## Regular file with more than one link

